In [7]:
#correlation Matrix

#dropping columns so that the matrix is only the rate values
corr_data=quitsdata.drop(['Total nonfarm.1','Mining and logging.1','Construction.1','Manufacturing.1','Trade, transportation, and utilities.1','Information.1','Financial activities.1','Professional and business services.1','Education and health services.1','Leisure and hospitality.1','Other services.1','Government.1'],axis=1)

#set the size of the figure
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"]=(8,8)

# use matplotlib.plot.matshow() to represent a correlation matrix in a new figure window
plt.matshow(corr_data.corr())

#set the ticks
plt.xticks(range(len(corr_data.columns)), corr_data.columns, rotation=90)
plt.xticks(range(len(corr_data.columns)), corr_data.columns)

#set the color bar
plt.colorbar()

#draw
plt.show()

In [9]:
#Scatter matrix
from pandas.plotting import scatter_matrix
axes = scatter_matrix(corr_data, alpha=0.2, figsize = (12, 12))

#to rotate labels
#code used was provided from this link: 
#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58623528/pandas-scatter-matrix-labels-vertical-x-and-horizontal-y-without-being-cut

for ax in axes.flatten():
    ax.xaxis.label.set_rotation(90)
    ax.yaxis.label.set_rotation(0)
    ax.yaxis.label.set_ha('right')
    
plt.tight_layout()
plt.gcf().subplots_adjust(wspace=0, hspace=0)
plt.show()
In [10]:
#renaming columns because the spaces and the names cause errors
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Total nonfarm':'TotalNonfarmRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Mining and logging':'MiningAndLoggingRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Construction':'ConstructionRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Manufacturing':'ManufacturingRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Trade, transportation, and utilities':'TradeTransportationAndUtilitiesRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Information':'InformationRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Financial activities':'FinancialActivitiesRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Professional and business services':'ProfessionalAndBusinessServicesRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Education and health services':'EducationAndHealthServicesRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Leisure and hospitality':'LeisureAndHospitalityRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Other services':'OtherServicesRate'}, inplace = True)
quitsdata.rename(columns = {'Government':'GovernmentRate'}, inplace = True)
In [11]:
#Time series line graph from 2001 - 2020
plt.rc('font', size=12)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(65, 20))

# Specify how our lines should look
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.TotalNonfarmRate, label='Total Nonfarm Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.MiningAndLoggingRate, label='Mining and Logging Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.ConstructionRate, label='Construction Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.ManufacturingRate, label='Manufacturing Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.TradeTransportationAndUtilitiesRate, label='Trade, Transportation, and Utilities Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.InformationRate, label='Information Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.FinancialActivitiesRate, label='Financial Activities Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.ProfessionalAndBusinessServicesRate, label='Professional And Business Services Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.EducationAndHealthServicesRate, label='Education and Health Services Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.LeisureAndHospitalityRate, label='Leisure and Hospitality Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.OtherServicesRate, label='Other Services Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.GovernmentRate, label='Government Rate')

ax.set_xlabel('Month')
ax.set_ylabel('Quit Rate')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
ax.set_title('Quit Rate by Industry for 2001 to AUG 2021')
ax.grid(True)
ax.legend(loc='upper left');

#Time series line graph Quit Rate by Industry 5 Year
plt.rc('font', size=12)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(27,13))

# Specify how our lines should look
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.TotalNonfarmRate, label='Total Nonfarm Rate', linestyle= 'dashed', marker='o')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.MiningAndLoggingRate, label='Mining and Logging Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.ConstructionRate, label='Construction Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.ManufacturingRate, label='Manufacturing Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.TradeTransportationAndUtilitiesRate, label='Trade, Transportation, and Utilities Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.InformationRate, label='Information Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.FinancialActivitiesRate, label='Financial Activities Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.ProfessionalAndBusinessServicesRate, label='Professional And Business Services Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.EducationAndHealthServicesRate, label='Education and Health Services Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.LeisureAndHospitalityRate, label='Leisure and Hospitality Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.OtherServicesRate, label='Other Services Rate')
ax.plot(quitsdata.Month, quitsdata.GovernmentRate, label='Government Rate')

#specifies to only plot data in this range on x axis
plt.xlim('Aug-16', 'Aug-21')

ax.set_xlabel('Month')
ax.set_ylabel('Quit Rate')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
ax.set_title('Quit Rate by Industry for AUG 2016 to AUG 2021')
ax.grid(True)
ax.legend(loc='upper left');

#covid cases line graph

#dropping columns
covidchart=coviddata.drop(['tot_cases','conf_cases','prob_cases','pnew_case','tot_death','conf_death','prob_death','pnew_death','new_death'],axis=1)

#date on x axis was showing in the wrong order
#this block of code reorders it
#Credit to:
#https://www.py4u.net/discuss/215386
field = "submission_date"
date_order = ["Jan-20", "Feb-20", "Mar-20", "Apr-20", "May-20", "Jun-20", "Jul-20", "Aug-20", "Sep-20", "Oct-20", "Nov-20", "Dec-20", "Jan-21", "Feb-21", "Mar-21", "Apr-21", "May-21", "Jun-21", "Jul-21", "Aug-21", "Sep-21", "Oct-21"]
ax = covidchart.set_index(field).loc[date_order].plot(kind="line", legend=False, figsize=(25,15))

ax.set_xlabel('Date')
ax.set_ylabel('New Covid Cases')
ax.set_title('Covid-19 Cases from Jan 2020 to Oct 2021')
#plt.xticks(coviddata.index, coviddata['submission_date'], rotation=(90))

In [48]:
x = combined.Month
y1 = combined.NewCovidCases
y2 = combined.TotalNonfarmRate

fig, ax1 = plt.subplots()

ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax1.bar(x, y1, color='r')
ax2.plot(x, y2, 'b-')

ax1.set_xlabel('Month')

ax1.set_ylabel('New Covid Cases', color='r')
ax2.set_ylabel('Total NonFarming Quit Rate', color='b')
ax1.set_title('Covid-19 New Cases and Total NonFarming Quit Rate from JAN 2020 to AUG 2021')

#rotate axis labels
#credit found here
#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19273040/rotating-axis-text-for-each-subplot/19273945
for ax in fig.axes:
    plt.sca(ax)
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)

plt.show()
